{{About|the firecracker}}
[[File:Common_Piccolo_packaging_in_the_Philippines.jpg|thumb|Sample piccolo packaging|210x210px]] '''Piccolo''' (also sold under the trade names '''Great Bawang''', '''Piccolo Corsair''' and numerous others) is a name given to a type of [[firecracker]] in the form of a thin small cylindrical stick filled with [[gunpowder]] and lit in the same way as a [[match]].
==Composition== Piccolo sticks ignite by rubbing the [[phosphorus]]-tipped head on a specially designed striking surface similar to a regular match, and can explode even on wet surfaces or underwater due to its thick cardboard shell.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}} They are usually sold in boxes with [[Piracy|pirate]]-themed artwork though variants exist with either generic or differently-themed packaging.
==Legality== As they are readily available and inexpensive, it has since earned notoriety as a leading cause of firecracker-related injuries in the [[Philippines]] especially among small children, either due to premature ignition or accidental ingestion.<ref name="Ducusin">{{cite news|url=http://www.journal.com.ph/news/nation/piccolo-still-top-cracker-injury-cause|title=Piccolo still top 'cracker' injury cause|last=Ducusin|first=Lee Ann|date=28 December 2015|work=Journal Online|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="Uy">{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/745525/doh-urges-ban-on-piccolo-firecracker|title=DOH urges ban on ‘piccolo’ firecracker|last=Uy|first=Jocelyn|date=8 December 2015|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="piccoloGMA">{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/549266/news/nation/piccolo-still-cause-of-most-firecracker-related-injuries-doh|title=Piccolo still cause of most firecracker-related injuries —DOH|date=28 December 2015|work=[[GMA News]]|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> The [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], along with the [[Bureau of Fire Protection]] and local government agencies, has taken steps to outlaw the sale and importation of piccolo sticks.<ref name="Crisostomo">{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/12/08/1530333/doh-seeks-strict-ban-piccolo|title=DOH seeks strict ban on piccolo|last=Crisostomo|first=Sheila|date=8 December 2015|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> [[Counterfeit consumer goods|Counterfeit]] and repackaged versions are being sold in [[flea market]]s and sidewalk stalls such as in [[Divisoria]], with most bearing patently false markings such as "Made in [[Bocaue, Bulacan|Bulacan]]" and instructions in [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] in an attempt to disguise its origin and thus evade detection by authorities.<ref name="ABSCBNPiccolo">{{cite news|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/12/29/14/banned-piccolo-pop-pop-seized-manila-port|title=Banned 'piccolo,' 'pop pop' seized in Manila port|date=29 December 2014|work=ABS-CBN News|publisher=[[ABS-CBN]]|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>
